About the conference : - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - The North Dakota State University ( NDSU ) Co- Laboratory for ATM Network Research and Development and the NDSU Database Systems User and Research Group ( DataSURG ) , both within the Department of Computer Science and Operation Research , will jointly hold the Second Annual ATM Networking Workshop and the Fourth Annual Mid-continent Information and Database Systems Conference ( MIDAS ) on May 10 - 12 , 1998 on the NDSU campus . The joint conference is partially supported by a grant from the National Science Foundation , North Dakota EPSCoR , NDSU Information Technology Services and the NDSU Department of Computer Science .
The joint ATM / MIDAS conference will focus on both theoretical and applied ATM networking issues . On the applied side , applications involving distributed database issues will be the main emphasis . A primary focus of the conference is to promote interaction between research and learning and targets students and faculty from college and university campuses , as well as employees of related technology companies .
The goal of the conference is to bring together experts in related areas to discuss progress and research issues in the design and implementation of ( 1 ) very high speed asynchronous transfer mode ( ATM ) communication networks , and ( 2 ) widely distributed DBMSs . The conference will include invited talks by several leading researchers in these areas , and the presentation of selected papers . Selected papers will appear in the conference proceedings .
Call for Papers : - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -
The ATM / MIDAS conference seeks papers on a variety of topics relating to distributed DBMSs and ATM networks , including ( 1 ) high speed network protocols , ( 2 ) distributed database management over high speed networks , ( 3 ) recent developments in video-on-demand research , ( 4 ) distance education over high speed networks , and ( 5 ) handling of remotely sensed data . The conference is being organized to encourage the free flow of ideas and facilitation of individualized discussions . Reports on experimental results and the presentation of new ideas or works-in-progress are particularly sought . Topics of general interest include :
* ATM protocol performance and analysis * QoS support in an ATM environment * Multicast and other scaleable services * New developments in video-on-demand * Distance education over ATM networks * QoS support for distributed DBMSs * Database and distributed database management * Heterogeneous distributed database management * Storage , transmission , and display of remotely sensed data * Precision agriculture applications of remotely sensed data * Data mining
Submission Guidelines : - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -
You are invited to submit a full paper in English for presentation at the workshop / conference . There will be a ten page limit on published papers . All submissions will be reviewed by the Program Committee . Papers accepted for presentation at the workshop will be included in a conference proceedings . Electronic submission in PostScript is also encouraged .
When submitting a paper , please include an abstract and a cover page with the name , address , telephone , fax , and e-mail address of the primary contact person . Submissions should be sent to :

Keynote Speakers : - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -
Dr . David H . C . Du , is a professor in the Department of Computer Science , University of Minnesota . Dr . Du is an active researcher in the US WEST COMPASS / Mercuri ATM trials and the MAGIC gigabit networking project . He was also an investigator in the High Definition Distance Learning ( HDDL ) project involving an ATM testbed for the purpose of remote education of medical students at various Minneapolis hospitals .
Dr . Sushil Jajodia , is Professor of Information and Software Systems Engineering and Director of Center for Secure Information Systems at the George Mason University , Fairfax , Virginia . Dr . Jajodia has directed the Database and Expert Systems Program at the National Science Foundation and headed the Database and Distributed Systems Section at the Naval Research Laboratory . He has extensive research in a wide range of topic areas of networking and data managment .
